collation.p: The manuscript is too fragile to be fully collated. However, as the textblock is more or less entirely detached from the binding, the quires, sixteen in all, can be counted at the spine. The first six quires have catchwords at intervals of 8 leaves, indicating a structure of quaternions.

p.note: Top left corner, in brown ink by an early modern hand: No 10; below: Brocmanni; centre page, in brown ink by an early modern hand, a note identifying the elevation of the feast of St George to festum duplex in November 1415: MCCCCXV in nov. Festivitas S. Georgii mart. ut duplex festum celebretur Stat. Seld. Tit. Hon. p. 574 ed. lat. Bottom of page, in brown ink by an early modern hand: Hunc librum dono mihi dedit pater carissimus .

binding.condition: The textblock is almost entirely detached from the binding. The leather is cracked at the spine and the bottom left front corner is frayed.

history.origin: England , 15th century, second half. The feasts listed in the calendar place the origin of the psalter in England. In a letter to the National Library dated , Dr A. I. Doyle of the Durham University Library, futhermore, identifies the gradings used in the calendar (prime dignitatis, secunde dignitatis) as those used by the Augustinian canons in England. Notable, therefore, is the celebration of the Augustinian St John of Bridlington as festum duplex on October 12. The Dedication of the church is celebrated on October 7. Based on the calendar's inclusion of the feast of St Osmund, canonized in , and the Transfiguration, instituted in , Doyle dates the manuscript to the third or fourth quarter of the 15th century.
history.provenance: Previously no. 10 in the collection of Nils Reinhold Brocman, book collector and librarian at the Royal Library and Antiquities Archive. Upon his death in , a large part of his book collection was donated to the Antiquities Archive (SBL).
A former owner's note in an early modern hand on states (in Latin) that the most beloved father gave me this book with the name of the donor having been erased.
On , an early modern hand has written in Swedish: Come Holy Spirit Lord God visit our hearts and give His Majesty's dutiful servant good spirits and a monogram, possibly RO.
history.acquisition: Transferred to the National Library from the Antiquities Archive.

p.note: In the margins, psalm numbers in ink in an early modern or near contemporary hand. Psalm 39 erroneously numbered as 29 (). Psalm 108 erroneously numbered as 107 (), and from here until Psalm 118 the numbering is off by one. Psalm 118:17 is numbered as 118, 118:33 as 119, 118:49 as 120, 118:65 as 121, 118:81 as 122, 118:97 as 123 (). After this, the numbering in ink disappears, but the numbering in pencil continues from Psalm 119 until the end.
Corrections of the erroneous psalm numbers in pencil in parentheses beneath each incorrect number. From Ps. 119 ff. (), psalm numbers in pencil in square brackets.

Covering the top half of the page, in black ink by and early modern hand: Kom Helige Ande Herre God besök wåra hiertan och gif Kongl.a Mai.tts tropliktig tienare godt mod; below, in the same ink and style, a large monogram: RO(?). Bottom right corner, in ink: a word, faded and difficult to make out.
Pen trials in the same hand and style as the recto: Denna and two flourished Rs (or Ks?).
